{"title_page": "2018 Giro d'Italia", "text_new": "{{about|the men's race|the women's race|2018 Giro d'Italia Femminile}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 2018 Giro d'Italia\n| series             = [[2018 UCI World Tour]]\n| race_no            = 21\n| season_no          = 38\n| image              = Giro d'Italia 2018 - Tel Aviv (2).jpg\n| image_caption      = The [[peloton]] on Stage 2 in [[Tel Aviv]]\n| image_alt          =\n| image_size         = 245px\n| date               = 4\u201327 May 2018\n| stages             = 21\n| distance           = 3572.4\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 89hr 02' 39\"\n| speed              = 40.1\n| first              = [[Chris Froome]]\n| first_nat          = GBR\n| first_team         = {{ct|SKY|2018}}\n| first_color        = pink\n| second             = [[Tom Dumoulin]]\n| second_nat         = NED\n| second_team        = {{ct|SUN|2018}}\n| third              = [[Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez (cyclist)|Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez]]\n| third_nat          = COL\n| third_team         = {{ct|AST|2018}}\n| points             = [[Elia Viviani]]\n| points_nat         = ITA\n| points_team        = {{ct|QST|2018}}\n| points_color       = violet\n| mountains          = [[Chris Froome]]\n| mountains_nat      = GBR\n| mountains_team     = {{ct|SKY|2018}}\n| mountains_color    = blue\n| youth              = [[Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez (cyclist)|Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez]]\n| youth_nat          = COL\n| youth_team         = {{ct|AST|2018}}\n| youth_color        = white\n| team               = {{ct|SKY|2018}}\n| teampoints         = \n| previous           = [[2017 Giro d'Italia|2017]]\n| next               = [[2019 Giro d'Italia|2019]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2018 Giro d'Italia''' was the 101st edition of the [[Giro d'Italia]], one of cycling's [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]] races. The race started in [[Jerusalem]] on 4 May, with a {{convert|9.7|km|0|abbr=on|adj=on}} [[individual time trial]] followed by two additional stages within [[Israel]]. After a rest day, there were 18 further stages in [[Italy]] before the tour reached the finish in [[Rome]] on 27 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/giro-ditalia-2018-will-begin-with-jerusalem-individual-time-trial/|title=Giro d\u2019Italia 2018 will begin with Jerusalem individual time trial - Cyclingnews.com|website=cyclingnews.com|accessdate=18 September 2017}}</ref> \n\nThe race was won by [[Team Sky]]'s [[Chris Froome]], the first British rider to win the race. In winning, Froome completed a hat-trick of consecutive [[Grand Tour]] victories, becoming the first rider since [[Bernard Hinault]] to hold all three Grand Tour titles simultaneously. His victory was highlighted by an audacious 80 km solo breakaway to win the mountainous stage 19; attacking the small group of leaders on the [[Cima Coppi]] of the 2018 Giro, the climb of the [[Colle delle Finestre]], he continued to extend his lead to the summit finish of [[Zoncolan]] and overturned a more than three minute deficit. The solo win, and the simultaneous implosion of race leader [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]], who lost more than 30 minutes on the day having lost contact on the first climb of the day, was described as \"one of the most extraordinary days in Giro d\u2019Italia history\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2018/may/25/giro-ditalia-2018-stage-19-live Giro d'Italia: Froome wins stunning stage 19 to take pink jersey \u2013 as it happened].</ref>.\n\n==History==\nThe Giro Big Start, touted as one of the most expensive sporting events in [[Israel]]'s history,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/with-spotlight-on-cycling-giro-ditalia-provides-much-needed-break-from-reality/|title=With spotlight on cycling, Giro d\u2019Italia provides much-needed break from reality|access-date=2018-05-28|language=en-US}}</ref> was largely financed by Canadian-Israeli mogul [[Sylvan Adams]] with the help of Israel's Tourism and Transportation Ministries. The 21-stage race began with a 10-kilometer time trial in [[Jerusalem]], followed by a 167-kilometer race from [[Haifa]] to [[Tel Aviv]], and a 229-kilometer race from [[Beersheba]] to [[Eilat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-gears-up-to-host-prestigious-giro-ditalia-cycling-race-opener-in-may/|title=Israel gears up to host prestigious Giro D\u2019Italia cycling race opener in May|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> They were the first stages of any [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]] event ever that have been held outside [[Europe]].\n\nThe 2018 Giro d'Italia Israel start was held to pay tribute to Italian cyclist [[Gino Bartali]], a three-time winner of the Giro d\u2019Italia. Bartali helped rescue hundreds of Italian Jews during the Holocaust and was recognized by [[Yad Vashem]] in 2013 as [[Righteous Among the Nations]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/notizie-ultima-ora/Atri_sport/Giro-2018-Lotti-omaggio-Bartali/18-09-2017/2-A_051879190.shtml?refresh_ce-cp|title=Giro 2018 Lotti omaggio Bartali|website=www.gazzetta.it|language=it|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref>\n\nThe race was won by {{ct|SKY|2018}}'s [[Chris Froome]], who therefore held all three Grand Tour titles simultaneously and became the first British cyclist to win the overall classification in the Giro. Froome crashed during a recon ride ahead of the prologue and lost time consistently over the first two weeks. In the final week, however, he won a stage that ended with the climb of [[Monte Zoncolan]], then took back several minutes on all his rivals in Stage 19 with a ride described as \"one for the history books\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Gregor|title='The closest comparison is with Coppi': Chris Froome's attack to win the Giro d'Italia was one for the history books|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/froomes-ride-best-thing-since-coppi-era-insiders-say-381353|accessdate=27 May 2018|work=Cycling Weekly|date=26 May 2018}}</ref> He ended up defeating the defending champion, [[Tom Dumoulin]], by 46 seconds.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/may/27/chris-froome-wins-giro-ditalia-rome-first-briton-british-winner-cycling|title =Chris Froome wins Giro d\u2019Italia in Rome to join cycling\u2019s exclusive club|date=27 May 2018|work=Guardian|accessdate=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main|List of teams and cyclists in the 2018 Giro d'Italia}}\nAll 18 [[List of 2017 UCI WorldTeams and riders|UCI WorldTeam]]s were automatically invited and were obliged to attend the race. Four wildcard [[UCI Professional Continental]] teams were also selected.{{sfn|''Garibaldi''|2017|p=12}} Each team started with eight riders (one less than in the previous year).\n\n[[Lotto\u2013Soudal]] chose to compete under a different name from the rest of the season: they became Lotto Fix ALL, using the name of a product made by Soudal, their normal sponsor.\n\nThe teams entering the race were:\n\n'''UCI WorldTeams'''\n{{div col|colwidth=20em|style=margin-right:20%;}}\n* {{ct|ALM|2018}}\n* {{ct|AST|2018}}\n* {{ct|TBM|2018}}\n* {{ct|BMC|2018}}\n* {{ct|BOH|2018}}\n* {{ct|EFD|2018}}\n* {{ct|DDD|2018}}\n* {{ct|FDJ|2018b}}\n* {{ct|KAT|2018}}\n* {{ct|TLJ|2018}}\n* [[Lotto\u2013Soudal|Lotto Fix ALL]]\n* {{ct|MOV|2018}}\n* {{ct|ORS|2018}}\n* {{ct|QST|2018}}\n* {{ct|SKY|2018}}\n* {{ct|SUN|2018}}\n* {{ct|TFS|2018}}\n* {{ct|UAD|2018}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n'''UCI Professional Continental teams'''\n{{div col|colwidth=20em|style=margin-right:20%;}}\n* {{ct|BRD|2018}}\n* {{ct|ANS|2018}}\n* {{ct|ICA|2018}}\n* {{ct|WIL|2018}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Pre-race favorites==\nThe main pre-race favorites were [[Chris Froome]] ({{ct|SKY|2018}}), defending champion [[Tom Dumoulin]] ({{ct|SUN|2018}}) and [[Fabio Aru]] ({{ct|UAE|2018}}). Other general classification contenders were [[Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez (cyclist)|Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez]] ({{ct|AST|2018}}), [[Thibaut Pinot]] ({{ct|FDJ|2018b}}), [[Wout Poels]] ({{ct|SKY|2018}}), [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]] and [[Esteban Chaves]] (both {{ct|ORS|2018}}), [[George Bennett (cyclist)|George Bennett]] ({{ct|TLJ|2018}}), [[Louis Meintjes]] ({{ct|DDD|2018}}), [[Michael Woods (cyclist)|Michael Woods]] ({{ct|EFD|2018}}), [[Davide Formolo]] ({{ct|BOH|2018}}), [[Rohan Dennis]] ({{ct|BMC|2018}}) and [[Domenico Pozzovivo]] ({{ct|TBM|2018}}).\n\nSprinters at the Giro included [[Elia Viviani]], [[Jakub Mareczko]], [[Niccolo Bonifazio]], [[Danny van Poppel]], [[Sacha Modolo]], [[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]], [[Jens Debusschere]] and [[Ryan Gibbons (cyclist)|Ryan Gibbons]].<ref name=pre1>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalcyclingnetwork.com/video/gcns-2017-giro-d-italia-preview-show|title=GCN's 2017 Giro d'Italia Preview Show}}</ref>\n\n==Route and stages==\n{{Main|2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11|2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+List of stages<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.velonews.com/2017/11/giro-ditalia/2018-giro-ditalia-route-will-challenge-froome-with-alpine-finale_452645/amp|title=Ample grandstands should keep journalists and fans alike out of the sun with the best possible views. - VeloNews.com|date=22 September 2006|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=col | Stage\n! scope=col | Date\n! scope=col | Course\n! scope=col | Distance\n! scope=col colspan=\"2\"|Type\n! scope=col | Winner\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |4 May\n| [[Jerusalem]] to Jerusalem\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|9.7|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]]\n| [[Individual time trial]]\n| {{flagathlete|[[Tom Dumoulin]]|NED}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |5 May\n| [[Haifa]] (Israel) to [[Tel Aviv]] (Israel)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|167|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Elia Viviani]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |6 May\n| [[Beersheba]] (Israel) to [[Eilat]] (Israel)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|229|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n|Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Elia Viviani]]|ITA}}\n|-\n!\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" |7 May\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''Rest day''\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|4\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |8 May\n| [[Catania]] to [[Caltagirone]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|202|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Hillystage.svg|22px]]\n| Hilly stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Tim Wellens]]|BEL}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|5\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |9 May\n| [[Agrigento]] to [[Santa Ninfa]] ([[Valle del Belice]]) \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|153|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Hillystage.svg|22px]]\n| Hilly stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Enrico Battaglin]]|ITA}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|6\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |10 May\n| [[Caltanissetta]] to [[Mount Etna]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|169|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Esteban Chaves]]|COL}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|7\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |11 May\n| [[Pizzo, Calabria|Pizzo]] to [[Praia a Mare]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|159|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]|IRL}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|8\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |12 May\n| [[Praia a Mare]] to [[Montevergine]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|209|km|0|abbr=on}}\n|[[File:Mediummountainstage.svg|22px|link=|alt=]]\n| Mid-mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Richard Carapaz]]|ECU}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|9\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |13 May\n| [[Pesco Sannita]] to [[Gran Sasso]] ([[Campo Imperatore]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|225|km|0|abbr=on}}\n|[[File:Mediummountainstage.svg|22px|link=|alt=]]\n| Mid-mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]|GBR}}\n|-\n!\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" |14 May\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''Rest day''\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|10\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |15 May\n| [[Penne, Abruzzo|Penne]] to [[Gualdo Tadino]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|244|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Hillystage.svg|22px]]\n| Hilly stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Matej Mohori\u010d]]|SLO}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|11\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |16 May\n| [[Assisi]] to [[Osimo]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|156|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Hillystage.svg|22px]]\n| Hilly stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]|GBR}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|12\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |17 May\n| [[Osimo]] to [[Imola]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|214|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]|IRL}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|13\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |18 May\n| [[Ferrara]] to [[Nervesa della Battaglia]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|180|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Elia Viviani]]|ITA}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|14\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |19 May\n| [[San Vito al Tagliamento]] to [[Monte Zoncolan]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|186|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Chris Froome]]|GBR}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|15\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |20 May\n| [[Tolmezzo]] to [[Sappada]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|176|km|0|abbr=on}}\n|[[File:Mediummountainstage.svg|22px|link=|alt=]]\n| Mid-mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]|GBR}}\n|-\n!\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" |21 May\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''Rest day''\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|16\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |22 May\n| [[Trento]] to [[Rovereto]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|34.2|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]]\n| [[Individual time trial]]\n| {{flagathlete|[[Rohan Dennis]]|AUS}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|17\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |23 May\n| [[Riva del Garda]] to [[Iseo, Lombardy|Iseo]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|149.5|km|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giroditalia.it/eng/news/viviani-poker-sotto-la-pioggia/|title=Four... midable Viviani! (the stage was shortened by 5.5&nbsp;km)|date=23 May 2018|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Elia Viviani]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|18\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |24 May\n| [[Abbiategrasso]] to [[Prato Nevoso]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|196|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maximilian Schachmann]]|GER}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|19\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |25 May\n| [[Venaria Reale]] to [[Bardonecchia]] (Monte Jafferau)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|185|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Chris Froome]]|GBR}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|20\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |26 May\n| [[Susa, Piedmont|Susa]] to [[Breuil-Cervinia|Cervinia]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|214|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Mikel Nieve]]|ESP}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|21\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |27 May\n| [[Rome]] to [[Rome]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|115|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]|IRL}}\n|}\n\n==Classification leadership==\n\nIn the Giro d'Italia, four different jerseys are awarded. The first and most important is the [[general classification in the Giro d'Italia|general classification]], calculated by adding each rider's finishing times on each stage. Riders receive time bonuses (10, 6 and 4 seconds respectively) for finishing in the first three places on each stage. Smaller time bonuses are also given to the top three riders at the last intermediate sprint on each stage (3, 2 and 1 seconds respectively). The rider with the lowest cumulative time is awarded the pink jersey ({{lang-it|maglia rosa}}),{{sfn|''Garibaldi''|2017|p=11}} and is considered the winner of the Giro d'Italia.<ref name=\"demystified\">{{cite news|first=Laura|last=Weislo|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/road/2008/giro08/?id=/features/2008/giro_classifications08|title=Giro d'Italia classifications demystified|date=13 May 2008|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=27 August 2009}}</ref><ref name=rulechanges>{{cite news|title=Giro revamps time bonus and points systems for 2014 edition|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2014/04/news/giro-revamps-time-bonus-points-systems-2014-edition_323335|accessdate=16 October 2015|work=[[VeloNews]]|publisher=[[Competitor Group, Inc.]]|date=8 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Points for the points classification\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=2 | Position\n! scope=\"col\" | 1\n! scope=\"col\" | 2\n! scope=\"col\" | 3\n! scope=\"col\" | 4\n! scope=\"col\" | 5\n! scope=\"col\" | 6\n! scope=\"col\" | 7\n! scope=\"col\" | 8\n! scope=\"col\" | 9\n! scope=\"col\" | 10\n! scope=\"col\" | 11\n! scope=\"col\" | 12\n! scope=\"col\" | 13\n! scope=\"col\" | 14\n! scope=\"col\" | 15\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 | Flat stages\n! Finish || 50 || 35 || 25 || 18 || 14 || 12 || 10 || 8 || 7 || 6 || 5 || 4 || 3 || 2 || 1\n|-\n! Intermediate Sprint || 20 || 12 || 8 || 6 || 4 || 3 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=7| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 | Hilly stages\n! Finish || 25 || 18 || 12 || 8 || 6 || 5 || 4 || 3 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=5| 0\n|-\n! Intermediate Sprint || 10 || 6 || 3 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=10| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 | Other stages\n! Finish || 15 || 12 || 9 || 7 || 6 || 5 || 4 || 3 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=5| 0\n|-\n! Intermediate Sprint || 8 || 4 || 1 ||colspan=12| 0\n|}\nAdditionally, there is a [[points classification in the Giro d'Italia|points classification]]. Riders win points for finishing in the top placings on each stage or by being within the first cyclists to reach intermediate sprint locations along each [[Mass start|mass-start]] stage. Flat stages award more points than mountainous stages, meaning that this classification tends to favour sprinters. The leader of the points classification wore the cyclamen jersey.{{sfn|''Garibaldi''|2017|p=11}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Points for the mountains classification\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Position\n! scope=\"col\" | 1\n! scope=\"col\" | 2\n! scope=\"col\" | 3\n! scope=\"col\" | 4\n! scope=\"col\" | 5\n! scope=\"col\" | 6\n! scope=\"col\" | 7\n! scope=\"col\" | 8\n! scope=\"col\" | 9\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Points for ''[[Colle delle Finestre|Cima Coppi]]''\n| 45 || 30 || 20 || 14 || 10 || 6 || 4 || 2 || 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Points for {{tooltip|Category 1|First-category climbs}}\n| 35 || 18 || 12 || 9 || 6 || 4 || 2 || 1 || 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Points for {{tooltip|Category 2|Second-category climbs}}\n| 15 || 8 || 6 || 4 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=3| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Points for {{tooltip|Category 3|Third-category climbs}}\n| 7 || 4 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=5| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Points for {{tooltip|Category 4|Fourth-category climbs}}\n| 3 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=6| 0\n|}\nThere is also a [[mountains classification in the Giro d'Italia|mountains classification]], for which points were awarded for reaching the top of a climb before other riders. Each climb was categorised as either first, second, third or fourth-category, with more points available for the more difficult, higher-categorised climbs. For first-category climbs, the top eight riders earned points; on second-category climbs, six riders won points; on third-category climbs, only the top four riders earned points with three on fourth-category climbs. The leadership of the mountains classification was marked by a blue jersey.{{sfn|''Garibaldi''|2017|p=11}} The ''[[Cima Coppi]]'', the race's highest point of elevation, awards more points than the other first-category climbs, with nine riders scoring points. At {{convert|2178|m}}, the ''Cima Coppi'' for the 2018 Giro d'Italia is the [[Colle delle Finestre]].\n\nThe fourth jersey represents the [[Young rider classification in the Giro d'Italia|young rider classification]]. This is decided the same way as the general classification, but only riders born after 1 January 1994 are eligible. The winner of the classification is awarded a white jersey.<ref name=\"demystified\" /> There are also [[Team classification in the Giro d'Italia|two classifications for teams]]. In the Trofeo Fast Team classification, the times of the best three cyclists per team on each stage are added up; the leading team is one with the lowest total time. The Trofeo Super Team is a team points classification, with the top 20 riders of each stage earning points for their team.<ref name=\"demystified\" />\n\nThe first additional award is the intermediate sprint classification. Each road stage has two sprints \u2013 the ''Traguardi Volanti''. The first 5 riders across the intermediate sprint lines are awarded points (10, 6, 3, 2 and 1 points respectively); the rider with the most points at the end of the race wins the classification. Another classification&nbsp;\u2013 the combativity prize ({{lang-it|Premio Combattivit\u00e0}})&nbsp;\u2013 involves points awarded to the first riders at the stage finishes, at intermediate sprints, and at the summits of categorised climbs. There is also a breakaway award ({{lang-it|Premio della Fuga}}). For this, points are awarded to each rider in any breakaway smaller than 10 riders that escapes for at least {{convert|5|km}}. Each rider is awarded a point for each kilometre that the rider was away from the peloton. The rider with the most points at the end of the Giro wins the award. The final classification is a \"fair play\" ranking for each team. Teams are given penalty points for infringing various rules. These range from half-point penalties, for offences that merit warnings from race officials, to a 2000-point penalty, for a positive doping test. The team that has the lowest points total at the end of the Giro wins the classification.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size:smaller;\"\n|+ Classification leadership by stage\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! style=\"width:14%;\"| Winner\n!  style=\"background:#efefef; width:14%;\"|[[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey pink.svg|25px]]\n!  style=\"background:#efefef; width:14%;\"|[[Points classification in the Giro d'Italia|Points classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey violet.svg|25px]]\n!  style=\"background:#efefef; width:14%;\"|[[Mountains classification in the Giro d'Italia|Mountains classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey blue.svg|25px]]\n!  style=\"background:#efefef; width:14%;\"|[[Young rider classification in the Giro d'Italia|Young rider classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey white.svg|25px]]\n!  style=\"background:#efefef; width:14%;\"|[[Team classification in the Giro d'Italia|General Super Team]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 1|1]]\n| [[Tom Dumoulin]]\n|style=\"background:pink;\"| [[Tom Dumoulin]]\n|style=\"background:violet;\"| [[Tom Dumoulin]]{{efn|name=Dumoulin|In stage 2, [[Rohan Dennis]], who was second in the points classification, wore the cyclamen jersey, because [[Tom Dumoulin]] (in first place) wore the pink jersey as leader of the general classification during that stage.}}\n|style=\"background:white;\"|''not awarded''\n|style=\"background:white;\" rowspan=5| [[Maximilian Schachmann]]\n|style=\"background:lightyellow;\" rowspan=3| {{ct|KAT|2018}}\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 2|2]]\n| [[Elia Viviani]]\n|style=\"background:pink;\" rowspan=4| [[Rohan Dennis]]\n|style=\"background:violet;\" rowspan=20| [[Elia Viviani]]\n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=4| [[Enrico Barbin]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 3|3]]\n| [[Elia Viviani]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 4|4]]\n| [[Tim Wellens]]\n| style=\"background:lightyellow;\" rowspan=10| {{ct|ORS|2018}}\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 5|5]]\n| [[Enrico Battaglin]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 6|6]]\n| [[Esteban Chaves]]\n|style=\"background:pink;\" rowspan=13| [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]] \n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=3| [[Esteban Chaves]]\n|style=\"background:white;\" rowspan=8| [[Richard Carapaz]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 7|7]]\n| [[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 8|8]]\n| [[Richard Carapaz]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 9|9]]\n| [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]\n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=10| [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]{{efn|name=Yates|From stage 10 to 15, [[Esteban Chaves]], who was second in the mountains classifications, wore the blue jersey, because [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]] (in first place) wore the pink jersey as leader of the general classification during this stages. For the same reason [[Giulio Ciccone]] wore the blue jersey from stage 16 to 18.}}\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 10|10]]\n| [[Matej Mohori\u010d]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 11|11]]\n| [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 12|12]]\n| [[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 13|13]]\n| [[Elia Viviani]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 14|14]]\n| [[Chris Froome]]\n|style=\"background:white;\" rowspan=8| [[Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez (cyclist)|Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez]]\n|style=\"background:lightyellow;\" rowspan=8| {{ct|SKY|2018}}\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 15|15]]\n| [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 16|16]]\n| [[Rohan Dennis]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 17|17]]\n| [[Elia Viviani]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 18|18]]\n| [[Maximilian Schachmann]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 19|19]]\n| [[Chris Froome]]\n|style=\"background:pink;\" rowspan=3| [[Chris Froome]]\n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=3| [[Chris Froome]]{{efn|name=Froome|In stage 20, [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]], who was second in the mountains classification, wore the blue jersey, because [[Chris Froome]] (in first place) wore the pink jersey as leader of the general classification during that stage. For the same reason [[Giulio Ciccone]] wore the blue jersey during stage 21.}}\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 20|20]]\n| [[Mikel Nieve]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 21|21]]\n| [[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]\n|-\n! colspan=2| Final\n!style=\"background:#F660AB;\"| [[Chris Froome]]\n!style=\"background:#B93B8F;| [[Elia Viviani]]\n!style=\"background:dodgerblue;\"| [[Chris Froome]]\n!style=\"background:offwhite;\"| [[Miguel 