\n|[[File:Mediummountainstage.svg|22px|link=|alt=]]\n| Mid-mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]|GBR}}\n|-\n!\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" |14 May\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''Rest day''\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|10\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |15 May\n| [[Penne, Abruzzo|Penne]] to [[Gualdo Tadino]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|244|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Hillystage.svg|22px]]\n| Hilly stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Matej Mohori\u010d]]|SLO}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|11\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |16 May\n| [[Assisi]] to [[Osimo]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|156|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Hillystage.svg|22px]]\n| Hilly stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]|GBR}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|12\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |17 May\n| [[Osimo]] to [[Imola]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|214|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]|IRL}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|13\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |18 May\n| [[Ferrara]] to [[Nervesa della Battaglia]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|180|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Elia Viviani]]|ITA}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|14\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |19 May\n| [[San Vito al Tagliamento]] to [[Monte Zoncolan]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|186|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Chris Froome]]|GBR}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|15\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |20 May\n| [[Tolmezzo]] to [[Sappada]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|176|km|0|abbr=on}}\n|[[File:Mediummountainstage.svg|22px|link=|alt=]]\n| Mid-mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]|GBR}}\n|-\n!\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" |21 May\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''Rest day''\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|16\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |22 May\n| [[Trento]] to [[Rovereto]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|34.2|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]]\n| [[Individual time trial]]\n| {{flagathlete|[[Rohan Dennis]]|AUS}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|17\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |23 May\n| [[Riva del Garda]] to [[Iseo, Lombardy|Iseo]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|149.5|km|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giroditalia.it/eng/news/viviani-poker-sotto-la-pioggia/|title=Four... midable Viviani! (the stage was shortened by 5.5&nbsp;km)|date=23 May 2018|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Elia Viviani]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|18\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |24 May\n| [[Abbiategrasso]] to [[Prato Nevoso]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|196|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maximilian Schachmann]]|GER}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|19\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |25 May\n| [[Venaria Reale]] to [[Bardonecchia]] (Monte Jafferau)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|185|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Chris Froome]]|GBR}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|20\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |26 May\n| [[Susa, Piedmont|Susa]] to [[Breuil-Cervinia|Cervinia]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|214|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Mikel Nieve]]|ESP}}\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"|21\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |27 May\n| [[Rome]] to [[Rome]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|115|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]|IRL}}\n|}\n\n==Classification leadership==\n\nIn the Giro d'Italia, four different jerseys are awarded. The first and most important is the [[general classification in the Giro d'Italia|general classification]], calculated by adding each rider's finishing times on each stage. Riders receive time bonuses (10, 6 and 4 seconds respectively) for finishing in the first three places on each stage. Smaller time bonuses are also given to the top three riders at the last intermediate sprint on each stage (3, 2 and 1 seconds respectively). The rider with the lowest cumulative time is awarded the pink jersey ({{lang-it|maglia rosa}}),{{sfn|''Garibaldi''|2017|p=11}} and is considered the winner of the Giro d'Italia.<ref name=\"demystified\">{{cite news|first=Laura|last=Weislo|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/road/2008/giro08/?id=/features/2008/giro_classifications08|title=Giro d'Italia classifications demystified|date=13 May 2008|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=27 August 2009}}</ref><ref name=rulechanges>{{cite news|title=Giro revamps time bonus and points systems for 2014 edition|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2014/04/news/giro-revamps-time-bonus-points-systems-2014-edition_323335|accessdate=16 October 2015|work=[[VeloNews]]|publisher=[[Competitor Group, Inc.]]|date=8 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Points for the points classification\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=2 | Position\n! scope=\"col\" | 1\n! scope=\"col\" | 2\n! scope=\"col\" | 3\n! scope=\"col\" | 4\n! scope=\"col\" | 5\n! scope=\"col\" | 6\n! scope=\"col\" | 7\n! scope=\"col\" | 8\n! scope=\"col\" | 9\n! scope=\"col\" | 10\n! scope=\"col\" | 11\n! scope=\"col\" | 12\n! scope=\"col\" | 13\n! scope=\"col\" | 14\n! scope=\"col\" | 15\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 | Flat stages\n! Finish || 50 || 35 || 25 || 18 || 14 || 12 || 10 || 8 || 7 || 6 || 5 || 4 || 3 || 2 || 1\n|-\n! Intermediate Sprint || 20 || 12 || 8 || 6 || 4 || 3 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=7| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 | Hilly stages\n! Finish || 25 || 18 || 12 || 8 || 6 || 5 || 4 || 3 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=5| 0\n|-\n! Intermediate Sprint || 10 || 6 || 3 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=10| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 | Other stages\n! Finish || 15 || 12 || 9 || 7 || 6 || 5 || 4 || 3 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=5| 0\n|-\n! Intermediate Sprint || 8 || 4 || 1 ||colspan=12| 0\n|}\nAdditionally, there is a [[points classification in the Giro d'Italia|points classification]]. Riders win points for finishing in the top placings on each stage or by being within the first cyclists to reach intermediate sprint locations along each [[Mass start|mass-start]] stage. Flat stages award more points than mountainous stages, meaning that this classification tends to favour sprinters. The leader of the points classification wore the cyclamen jersey.{{sfn|''Garibaldi''|2017|p=11}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Points for the mountains classification\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Position\n! scope=\"col\" | 1\n! scope=\"col\" | 2\n! scope=\"col\" | 3\n! scope=\"col\" | 4\n! scope=\"col\" | 5\n! scope=\"col\" | 6\n! scope=\"col\" | 7\n! scope=\"col\" | 8\n! scope=\"col\" | 9\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Points for ''[[Colle delle Finestre|Cima Coppi]]''\n| 45 || 30 || 20 || 14 || 10 || 6 || 4 || 2 || 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Points for {{tooltip|Category 1|First-category climbs}}\n| 35 || 18 || 12 || 9 || 6 || 4 || 2 || 1 || 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Points for {{tooltip|Category 2|Second-category climbs}}\n| 15 || 8 || 6 || 4 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=3| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Points for {{tooltip|Category 3|Third-category climbs}}\n| 7 || 4 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=5| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Points for {{tooltip|Category 4|Fourth-category climbs}}\n| 3 || 2 || 1 ||colspan=6| 0\n|}\nThere is also a [[mountains classification in the Giro d'Italia|mountains classification]], for which points were awarded for reaching the top of a climb before other riders. Each climb was categorised as either first, second, third or fourth-category, with more points available for the more difficult, higher-categorised climbs. For first-category climbs, the top eight riders earned points; on second-category climbs, six riders won points; on third-category climbs, only the top four riders earned points with three on fourth-category climbs. The leadership of the mountains classification was marked by a blue jersey.{{sfn|''Garibaldi''|2017|p=11}} The ''[[Cima Coppi]]'', the race's highest point of elevation, awards more points than the other first-category climbs, with nine riders scoring points. At {{convert|2178|m}}, the ''Cima Coppi'' for the 2018 Giro d'Italia is the [[Colle delle Finestre]].\n\nThe fourth jersey represents the [[Young rider classification in the Giro d'Italia|young rider classification]]. This is decided the same way as the general classification, but only riders born after 1 January 1994 are eligible. The winner of the classification is awarded a white jersey.<ref name=\"demystified\" /> There are also [[Team classification in the Giro d'Italia|two classifications for teams]]. In the Trofeo Fast Team classification, the times of the best three cyclists per team on each stage are added up; the leading team is one with the lowest total time. The Trofeo Super Team is a team points classification, with the top 20 riders of each stage earning points for their team.<ref name=\"demystified\" />\n\nThe first additional award is the intermediate sprint classification. Each road stage has two sprints \u2013 the ''Traguardi Volanti''. The first 5 riders across the intermediate sprint lines are awarded points (10, 6, 3, 2 and 1 points respectively); the rider with the most points at the end of the race wins the classification. Another classification&nbsp;\u2013 the combativity prize ({{lang-it|Premio Combattivit\u00e0}})&nbsp;\u2013 involves points awarded to the first riders at the stage finishes, at intermediate sprints, and at the summits of categorised climbs. There is also a breakaway award ({{lang-it|Premio della Fuga}}). For this, points are awarded to each rider in any breakaway smaller than 10 riders that escapes for at least {{convert|5|km}}. Each rider is awarded a point for each kilometre that the rider was away from the peloton. The rider with the most points at the end of the Giro wins the award. The final classification is a \"fair play\" ranking for each team. Teams are given penalty points for infringing various rules. These range from half-point penalties, for offences that merit warnings from race officials, to a 2000-point penalty, for a positive doping test. The team that has the lowest points total at the end of the Giro wins the classification.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size:smaller;\"\n|+ Classification leadership by stage\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! style=\"width:14%;\"| Winner\n!  style=\"background:#efefef; width:14%;\"|[[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey pink.svg|25px]]\n!  style=\"background:#efefef; width:14%;\"|[[Points classification in the Giro d'Italia|Points classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey violet.svg|25px]]\n!  style=\"background:#efefef; width:14%;\"|[[Mountains classification in the Giro d'Italia|Mountains classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey blue.svg|25px]]\n!  style=\"background:#efefef; width:14%;\"|[[Young rider classification in the Giro d'Italia|Young rider classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey white.svg|25px]]\n!  style=\"background:#efefef; width:14%;\"|[[Team classification in the Giro d'Italia|General Super Team]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 1|1]]\n| [[Tom Dumoulin]]\n|style=\"background:pink;\"| [[Tom Dumoulin]]\n|style=\"background:violet;\"| [[Tom Dumoulin]]{{efn|name=Dumoulin|In stage 2, [[Rohan Dennis]], who was second in the points classification, wore the cyclamen jersey, because [[Tom Dumoulin]] (in first place) wore the pink jersey as leader of the general classification during that stage.}}\n|style=\"background:white;\"|''not awarded''\n|style=\"background:white;\" rowspan=5| [[Maximilian Schachmann]]\n|style=\"background:lightyellow;\" rowspan=3| {{ct|KAT|2018}}\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 2|2]]\n| [[Elia Viviani]]\n|style=\"background:pink;\" rowspan=4| [[Rohan Dennis]]\n|style=\"background:violet;\" rowspan=20| [[Elia Viviani]]\n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=4| [[Enrico Barbin]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 3|3]]\n| [[Elia Viviani]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 4|4]]\n| [[Tim Wellens]]\n| style=\"background:lightyellow;\" rowspan=10| {{ct|ORS|2018}}\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 5|5]]\n| [[Enrico Battaglin]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 6|6]]\n| [[Esteban Chaves]]\n|style=\"background:pink;\" rowspan=13| [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]] \n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=3| [[Esteban Chaves]]\n|style=\"background:white;\" rowspan=8| [[Richard Carapaz]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 7|7]]\n| [[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 8|8]]\n| [[Richard Carapaz]]\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 9|9]]\n| [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]\n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=10| [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]]{{efn|name=Yates|From stage 10 to 15, [[Esteban Chaves]], who was second in the mountains classifications, wore the blue jersey, because [[Simon Yates (cyclist)|Simon Yates]] (in first place) wore the pink jersey as leader of the general classification during this stages. For the same reason [[Giulio Ciccone]] wore the blue jersey from stage 16 to 18.}}\n|-\n! [[2018 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 