{"title_page": "Arielle Charnas", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Arielle Charnas\n| birth_name         = Arielle Noa Nachmani\n| birth_place        = [[Old Westbury, New York|Old Westbury]], New York\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Fashion blogger\n* Influencer\n* Designer\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|https://somethingnavy.com/}}\n}}\n'''Arielle Noa Charnas''' is an American [[fashion blog]]ger and [[Fashion influencer|influencer]]. She is known for starting the blog and Instagram account Something Navy, launched in 2009.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/05/fashion/arielle-noa-charnas-something-navy-make-up-skin-care.html|title=How to Prep for the Front Row, and Beyond|last=Shapiro|first=Bee|date=2017-09-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/now-you-too-can-get-1-million-instagram-followers-1515599740|title=What Happens When You Reach a Million Instagram Followers|last=Crain|first=Abbey|date=2018-01-10|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Charnas also designs a line of apparel in partnership with [[Nordstrom]].<ref name = wwd2>{{cite web | url = https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-features/somethingnavy-arielle-charnas-nordstrom-partner-on-standalone-somethingnavy-brand-1202595986/ | publisher = WWD | title = Arielle Charnas Bows Something Navy Brand With Nordstrom| accessdate = 26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nDiet Prada should stop editing this!\n\n== Career ==\nIn 2009, Charnas began posting photos of her outfits and showcasing her personal style online on a blog started, named ''Something Navy''.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessoffashion.com/articles/professional/influencers-are-investors-now-too|title=Influencers Are Investors Now, Too|last=Strugatz|first=Rachel|date=2018-11-01|website=The Business of Fashion|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessoffashion.com/articles/professional/is-arielle-charnas-the-future-of-fashion|title=Is Arielle Charnas the Future of Fashion?|last=Strugatz|first=Rachel|date=2018-10-11|website=The Business of Fashion|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> She describes her personal style as \"elevated basic\".<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-features/somethingnavy-arielle-charnas-nordstrom-partner-on-standalone-somethingnavy-brand-1202595986/|title=Arielle &nbsp;Charnas Bows SomethingNavy Brand With Nordstrom|last=Strugatz|first=Rachel|date=2018-02-26|website=Women's Wear Daily|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> She first started the blog to impress her boyfriend at the time. They broke up but Charnas continued to blog on her website and began posting on Instagram, a new social media platform at the time.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://fashionista.com/2018/09/something-navy-arielle-charnas-career|title=How Arielle Charnas Turned Her Blog, 'Something Navy,' Into a Lifestyle Brand|last=McCall|first=Tyler|date=2018-09-24|website=Fashionista|language=en|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>\n\nBefore her blog gained in popularity, Charnas worked at a [[Theory (clothing retailer)|Theory]] store in the [[Meatpacking District, Manhattan|Meatpacking District]].<ref name=\":2\" /> She later signed a four-year endorsement deal with [[TRESemm\u00e9]] and appeared in television ads for the shampoo brand that began airing in January 2016.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nCharnas later launched her first collection of apparel with [[Nordstrom]] in fall 2017.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/schmooze/403643/arielle-charnas-of-something-navy-gets-real-about-gory-details-of/|title=Arielle Charnas of \u2018Something Navy\u2019 Shares The Gory Details of Childbirth|last=Azoulay|first=Bonnie|date=2018-06-20|website=The Forward|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> Her first fashion line named Something Navy X Treasure & Bond was launched on September 25, 2017, in 52 Nordstrom stores across the United States and Canada. The collection included 30 ready-to-wear outfits, including shoes and accessories.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/fashion/la-ig-wwd-arielle-charnas-nordstrom-20170828-story.html|title=Influence peddler: Arielle Charnas teams with Nordstrom for collection|last=Strugatz|first=Rachel|date=2017-08-28|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> Sales online exceeded over a million dollars in the first 24 hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-features/superinfluencer-something-navy-nordstrom-drives-millions-in-sales-11009231/|title=\u2018Superinfluencer\u2019 Something Navy Soars at Nordstrom|last=Strugatz|first=Rachel|date=2017-09-29|website=Women's Wear Daily|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> She also made personal appearances at Nordstrom stores in Chicago and New York to promote the collection.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nBy September 2017, she had over one million followers on Instagram.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Shapiro|first=Bee|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/05/fashion/arielle-noa-charnas-something-navy-make-up-skin-care.html|title=How to Prep for the Front Row, and Beyond|date=2017-09-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In February 2018, Charnas signed a long-term contract with Nordstrom to license Something Navy and her likeness, as well as establish a stand-alone brand.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/something-navy-arielle-charnas-nordstrom-influencers-are-the-best-way-to-keep-retail-alive/|title=Something Navy's Arielle Charnas: \"Influencers are the best way to keep retail alive\"|date=March 25, 2019|website=CBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> In March 2018, a single Instagram story promoting Bandier, an [[Sportswear (activewear)|activewear]] retailer in which Charnas owns a small stake,<ref name=\":4\" /> generated over $207,000 in sales in just four hours.<ref name=\":1\" /> In September 2018, Something Navy released Charnas\u2019 second collection of apparel with Nordstrom and the first under the stand-alone brand. On the launch date, high traffic temporarily shut down the Nordstrom website an hour after the collection's release but sales for the day reportedly reached between $4 to $5 million.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/something-navy-crashes-site-beats-expectations-nordstrom-1202845078/|title=Something &nbsp;Navy Crashes Site, Beats Expectations at Nordstrom|last=Lockwood|first=Lisa|date=2018-09-25|website=Women's Wear Daily|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> In August 2019, it was announced that Charnas raised $10 million in funding from investors, valuing the Something Navy brand at nearly $45 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessoffashion.com/articles/professional/the-billionaire-who-backed-michael-kors-is-investing-in-influencer-arielle-charnas|title=The Billionaire Who Backed Michael Kors Is Investing in Influencer Arielle Charnas|date=2019-08-15|website=The Business of Fashion|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/life-culture/article/48577/1/influencer-tested-positive-covid-19-arielle-charnas-instagram-coronavirus|title=Influencer tests positive for COVID-19, then posts a picture outside|date=Mar 30, 2020|website=Dazed|accessdate=Apr 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCharnas was born in [[Old Westbury, New York|Old Westbury]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She married Brandon Charnas on October 18, 2014, in [[Fisher Island, Florida|Fisher Island]], [[Florida]].<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brides.com/story/arielle-nachmani-something-navy-wedding-photos-fred-marcus-studio|title=*Something Navy*'s Arielle Nachmani's Chic Miami Wedding Photos|last=Mackey|first=Jaimie|date=2014-12-03|website=Brides|language=en|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> The couple has two daughters, Ruby Lou and Esme Rae.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2018/12/something-navy-star-arielle-charnas-launching-nordstrom-holiday-line/|title=Something Navy\u2019s Arielle Charnas Is More Successful Than Ever\u2014But at What Price?|last=Curotto|first=Merin|date=2018-12-12|website=Observer|language=en|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Charnas announced she tested positive for COVID-19 after using her personal connections to get a COVID-19 test at a time when limited tests were available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/26/821582951/is-loss-of-smell-and-taste-a-symptom-of-covid-19-doctors-want-to-find-out|title=Is Loss Of Smell And Taste A Symptom Of COVID-19? Doctors Want To Find Out|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/17/influencer-uses-personal-connections-to-get-coronavirus-test/|title=Influencer uses personal connections to get coronavirus test|last=Dellatto|first=Marisa|date=2020-03-17|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> She received criticism for going against CDC guidelines by not self-quarantining and by traveling with her family to the Hamptons eight days after her diagnosis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indy100.com/article/coronavirus-influencer-arielle-charnas-breaks-self-isolation-quarantine-9440396|title=Influencer Arielle Charnas slammed for going on Hamptons trip after revealing she has coronavirus in test she got from a 'doctor friend'|last=Staples|first=Louis|date=April 1, 2020|work=Indy100|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, Nordstrom further disassociated themselves from Charnas by announcing \"Our Partnership with Arielle Charnas ended in 2019. We have no foreseeable Something Navy collaborations\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/stephaniemcneal/arielle-charnas-coronavirus-instagram-controversy|title=How Influencer Arielle Charnas Became The Face Of \"Privilege In The Age Of The Coronavirus\"|website=BuzzFeed News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The New York Post labelled her a \"Covidiot\" and Vanity Fair (magazine) questioned if her decisions during the Pandemic would be the end of her \"Influencer\" career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/02/covidiot-blogger-arielle-charnas-may-have-ruined-her-brand/|title=\u2018Covidiot\u2019 blogger Arielle Charnas may have ruined her brand|last=Schrader|first=Adam|date=2020-04-03|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2020/04/influencers-coronavirus-arielle-charnas-escape-new-york|title=Is This the End of Influencing as We Knew It?|last=Bryant|first=Kenzie|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website|https://somethingnavy.com/}}\n* {{Instagram|id=ariellecharnas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charnas, Arielle}}\n[[Category:American fashion designers]]\n[[Category:American Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:American women bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:Fashion influencers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Nassau County, New York]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Arielle Charnas\n| birth_name         = Arielle Noa Nachmani\n| birth_place        = [[Old Westbury, New York|Old Westbury]], New York\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Fashion blogger\n* Influencer\n* Designer\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|https://somethingnavy.com/}}\n}}\n'''Arielle Noa Charnas''' is an American [[fashion blog]]ger and [[Fashion influencer|influencer]]. She is known for startin